The Toyplot Tutorial¶

Getting Started¶

Welcome! This tutorial will introduce you to the basics of working with Toyplot.

Note: This tutorial was created in an IPython notebook and assumes that you’re following-along in a notebook of your own. If you aren’t using a notebook, you should jump ahead to the section on Rendering for some important information on how to display your figures.

To begin, we’re going to import numpy (so we can create data to use for our figures), and the main toyplot module:

import numpy
import toyplot

For our first figure, let’s create a simple set of X and Y coordinates that we can plot:

x = numpy.linspace(0, 10)
y = x ** 2

Now, we put Toyplot to work ...

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=300, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.plot(x, y)

Short as it is, this example demonstrates several key features of Toyplot:

  • Toyplot figures are beautiful, scalable, embeddable, and interactive. Try mousing over the above figure, and zoom it using your browser controls. Note that Toyplot produces a clean, aesthetically pleasing figure that is crisp at any scale and free of chartjunk “out-of-the-box”.
  • Every Toyplot figure begins with a canvas - a drawing area upon which the caller adds marks. Note that the width and height of the canvas have been specified in dimensionless drawing units, which are translated into concrete units when the canvas is rendered by a backend.
  • A Toyplot figure typically contains one-or-more sets of axes which map a data domain into canvas drawing units.
  • Marks are added to axes using factory functions provided by the axes. In this example, the plot function creates a line mark using the supplied coordinates. Note that the axes have been automatically sized to the data’s domain.

Styles¶

Let’s say that you wanted to alter the above figure to make the plotted line blue and dashed. To do so, simply override the default style information when creating the plot:

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=300, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.plot(x, y, style={"stroke":"blue", "stroke-dasharray":"2, 2"})

In this case, you can see that the style information is a dictionary of key-value properties that alter how a mark is rendered. To avoid reinventing the wheel, Toyplot uses Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) to specify styles. If you’re familiar with web development, you already know CSS. If not, this tutorial will cover many of most useful CSS properties for Toyplot as we go, and there are many learning resources for CSS online.

Every mark you add to a figure will have at least one (possibly more than one) set of styles that control its appearance.

Plotting¶

Let’s continue with the previous example. As a shortcut, you can omit the X coordinates when using the plot command, and a set of coordinates in the range \([0, n)\) will be provided (compare the X axis with the previous plots to see the difference):

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=300, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.plot(y)

If you plot multiple series, each plot automatically receives a different color:

x = numpy.linspace(0, 10)
y1 = numpy.sin(x)
y2 = numpy.cos(x)
y3 = numpy.sin(x) + numpy.cos(x)

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=600, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark1 = axes.plot(x, y1)
mark2 = axes.plot(x, y2)
mark3 = axes.plot(x, y3)

As we’ve already seen, we can use the “stroke” style to override the default color of each plot; in addition, the “stroke-width” and “stroke-opacity” styles are useful properties for (de)emphasizing individual plots:

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=600, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark1 = axes.plot(x, y1, style={"stroke-width":1, "stroke-opacity":0.6})
mark2 = axes.plot(x, y2, style={"stroke-width":1, "stroke-opacity":0.6})
mark3 = axes.plot(x, y3)

Palettes¶

Before proceeding, let’s take a moment to look at how the default color for a mark is assigned. When we add multiple marks to a set of axes, each mark gets a different color. These default colors are all drawn from a palette - an ordered collection of RGBA colors. For example, here’s Toyplot’s default palette:

import toyplot.color
toyplot.color.Palette()

Note: Like canvases, palettes are automatically rendered in IPython notebooks, in this case as a collection of color swatches.

You should observe that the order of colors in the palette match the order of the colors that were assigned to our plots as they were added to their axes. You could create a custom palette by passing a sequence of colors (CSS colors, RGB tuples or RGBA tuples) to the toyplot.color.Palette constructor, but Toyplot already comes with a builtin collection of high-quality palettes from Color Brewer, which we strongly recommend for most work:

print numpy.array(toyplot.color.brewer.names())

['Accent' 'Blues' 'BrBG' 'BuGn' 'BuPu' 'Dark2' 'GnBu' 'Greens' 'Greys'
 'OrRd' 'Oranges' 'PRGn' 'Paired' 'Pastel1' 'Pastel2' 'PiYG' 'PuBu'
 'PuBuGn' 'PuOr' 'PuRd' 'Purples' 'RdBu' 'RdGy' 'RdPu' 'RdYlBu' 'RdYlGn'
 'Reds' 'Set1' 'Set2' 'Set3' 'Spectral' 'YlGn' 'YlGnBu' 'YlOrBr' 'YlOrRd']

toyplot.color.brewer("RdYlBu")

Note that you can reverse the order of any palette:

toyplot.color.brewer("RdYlBu", reverse=True)

Also, keep in mind that each Color Brewer palette comes in several variants with different numbers of colors:

toyplot.color.brewer.counts("RdYlBu")

[3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11]

toyplot.color.brewer("RdYlBu", 5)

Now that we know how palettes work in Toyplot, we’ll start using them in the examples that follow.

Filled Regions¶

You can use fill to display a region bounded by two sets of Y coordinates. This can be a handy way to visualize data distributions:

numpy.random.seed(1234)
observations = numpy.random.normal(size=(50, 50))

x = numpy.linspace(0, 1, len(observations))
y1 = numpy.min(observations, axis=1)
y2 = numpy.max(observations, axis=1)

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=400, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.fill(x, y1, y2)

Use the “fill” style (not to be confused with the fill command) to control the color of the shaded region. You might also want to change the fill-opacity or add a stroke using styles:

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=400, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.fill(x, y1, y2, style={"fill":"steelblue", "fill-opacity":0.5, "stroke":"black"})

As with plots, you can omit the X coordinates, which will default to the range \([0, n)\):

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=400, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.fill(y1, y2)

If you only specify one boundary the second will be set to \(y = 0\):

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=400, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.fill(y2)

Toyplot also makes it easy to define multiple sets of boundaries, by passing an \(M \times N\) matrix as input, where \(M\) is the number of observations, and \(N\) is the number of boundaries:

boundaries = numpy.column_stack(
    (numpy.min(observations, axis=1),
     numpy.percentile(observations, 25, axis=1),
     numpy.percentile(observations, 50, axis=1),
     numpy.percentile(observations, 75, axis=1),
     numpy.max(observations, axis=1)))

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=400, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.fill(boundaries)

You can think of fill (and other types of) marks as containers for collections of series, where in this case, \(n\) boundaries define \(n-1\) series.

This distinction is important because we can control the style of individual series, not just the mark as a whole. So, if we want to override the default colors for the bars, we can do it using the mark’s global “fill” style (with a stroke to display the boundaries between series):

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=400, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.fill(boundaries, style={"fill":"steelblue", "stroke":"white"})

... or we can do it using the “fill” argument:

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=400, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.fill(boundaries, fill="steelblue", style={"stroke":"white"})

The advantage of the latter approach is that the “fill” argument can specify a sequence of color values, one-per-series. And, you can combine those per-series fill values with global styles:

fill = ["red", "green", "blue", "yellow"]

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=400, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.fill(boundaries, fill=fill, style={"stroke":"black"})

The “opacity” and “title” arguments can also be specified on a per-series basis (hover the mouse over the fill regions in the following figure to see the title as a popup):

fill = ["blue", "blue", "red", "red"]
opacity = [0.1, 0.2, 0.2, 0.1]
title = ["1st Quartile", "2nd Quartile", "3rd Quartile", "4th Quartile"]

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=400, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.fill(boundaries, fill=fill, opacity=opacity, title=title, style={"stroke":"black"})

In the preceding examples you defined the fill regions by explicitly specifying their boundaries ... as an alternative, you can generate fills by specifying the heights of each region (note that \(n\) heights define \(n\) series):

numpy.random.seed(1234)

heights = []
x = numpy.linspace(0, 4 * numpy.pi, 100)
for i in range(10):
    heights.append(numpy.random.uniform(0.1, 1) * (2 + numpy.sin(numpy.random.normal() + (numpy.random.normal() * x))))
heights = numpy.column_stack(heights)

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=500, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
m = axes.fill(heights, baseline="stacked")

If you pass a sequence of scalar values instead of colors to the “fill” argument, the values will be mapped to colors using a linear mapping and a default sequential palette:

fill = numpy.arange(heights.shape[1])

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=500, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
m = axes.fill(heights, baseline="stacked", fill=fill)

Of course, you’re free to supply your own palette for the mapping:

palette = toyplot.color.brewer("RdBu")

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=500, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
m = axes.fill(heights, baseline="stacked", fill=fill, palette=palette)

... note that the baseline parameter is what signals that the inputs are heights instead of boundaries. You can also change the baseline parameter to create various types of streamgraph:

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=500, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
m = axes.fill(heights, baseline="symmetric", fill=fill, palette=palette)

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=500, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
m = axes.fill(heights, baseline="wiggle", fill=fill, palette=palette)

Barplots¶

Of course, you can’t have a plotting library without barplots ...

heights = numpy.linspace(1, 10, 10) ** 2

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=300, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.bars(heights)

By default the bars are centered on integer X coordinates in the range \([0, n)\) with their width set to provide a small gap between bars - but we can specify our own X coordinates and width to suit:

x, width = numpy.linspace(-2, 2, 20, retstep=True)
y = 5 - (x ** 2)

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=300, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.bars(x, y, width=width * 0.3)

As a convenience, you can pass the output from numpy.histogram() directly to toyplot.Axes2D.bars():

numpy.random.seed(1234)
population = numpy.random.normal(size=10000)

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=300, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
bars = axes.bars(numpy.histogram(population, 20))

Like fills, Toyplot allows you to stack multiple sets of bars, by passing an \(M \times N\) matrix as input, where \(M\) is the number of observations, and \(N\) is the number of series:

heights1 = numpy.linspace(1, 10, 10) ** 1.1
heights2 = numpy.linspace(1, 10, 10) ** 1.3
heights3 = numpy.linspace(1, 10, 10) ** 1.4
heights4 = numpy.linspace(1, 10, 10) ** 1.5
heights = numpy.column_stack((heights1, heights2, heights3, heights4))

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=300, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.bars(heights)

As before, we can style the bars globally or use the “fill” argument to specify per-series colors:

fill = ["red", "green", "blue", "yellow"]
style = {"stroke":"black"}

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=300, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
bars = axes.bars(heights, fill=fill, style=style)

The “opacity” and “title” arguments can also be specified on a per-series basis (hover the mouse over the bars in the following figure to see the title as a popup):

opacity = [0.2, 1.0, 0.2, 0.2]
title = ["Series 1", "Series 2", "Series 3", "Series 4"]

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=300, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
bars = axes.bars(heights, fill=fill, opacity=opacity, title=title, style=style)

If you pass a sequence of scalar values to the “fill” argument, the values will be mapped to colors using a linear mapping and a default sequential palette:

fill = numpy.arange(heights.shape[1])

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=300, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
bars = axes.bars(heights, fill=fill, style=style)

Of course, you’re free to supply your own palette for the mapping:

palette = toyplot.color.brewer("Purples")

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=300, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
bars = axes.bars(heights, fill=fill, palette=palette, style=style)

Scatterplots¶

Next in our list of marks is the scatterplot:

numpy.random.seed(1234)
x1 = numpy.random.normal(loc=-2, size=200)
y1 = numpy.random.normal(size=len(x1))

x2 = numpy.random.normal(loc=2, size=200)
y2 = numpy.random.normal(size=len(x2))

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=500, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark1 = axes.scatterplot(x1, y1)
mark2 = axes.scatterplot(x2, y2)

You can use a scatterplot by itself to display data, or you can use it to highlight the individual datums in a regular plot:

x = numpy.linspace(0, 2 * numpy.pi)
y1 = numpy.sin(x)
y2 = numpy.cos(x)

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=500, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
line1 = axes.plot(x, y1)
points1 = axes.scatterplot(x, y1)
line2 = axes.plot(x, y2)
points2 = axes.scatterplot(x, y2)

As you might expect, you can omit the X coordinates for a scatterplot, and they will fall in to the range \([0, n)\):

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=500, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.scatterplot(y1)

Like a barplot, you can control the fill and size of a scatterplot either globally or per-datum (note that the size is treated as an approximation of the area of an individual datum):

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=500, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.scatterplot(y1, fill="steelblue", size=49)

fill = numpy.arange(len(x))
size = numpy.linspace(1, 100, len(x))

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=500, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.scatterplot(y1, fill=fill, size=size, style={"stroke":"black"})

Markers¶

You can choose from a variety of marker shapes for a scatterplot:

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=500, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark1 = axes.scatterplot(y1, size=50, marker="+", style={"stroke":"black"})
mark1 = axes.scatterplot(y2, size=50, marker="^")

So far, we’ve seen that a single scatterplot can encode up to four data dimensions - X, Y, fill (color), and size. Using per-datum markers, you can encode a fifth dimension. Let’s use this to create a chart of all the marker shapes supported by Toyplot:

x, y = numpy.meshgrid(numpy.arange(5), numpy.arange(3, -1, -1))
x, y = numpy.ravel(x), numpy.ravel(y)
marker = ["","|","-","+","x","*","^",">","v","<","s","d","o","oo","o|","o-","o+","ox","o*",""]
marker_style = {"fill":"yellow", "stroke":"black"}

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=300, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes(show=False)
mark = axes.scatterplot(x, y, marker=marker, size=100, style=marker_style)

In addition to the basic marker shapes, you can create your own by adding text labels:

x = numpy.linspace(0, 10, 100)
y1 = x ** 1.1
y2 = 10 + x ** 1.5
y3 = 20 + x ** 2
marker_style = {"fill":"white", "stroke":"black"}

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=500, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
line1 = axes.plot(x, y1)
m1 = axes.scatterplot(x[::10], y1[::10], marker=("o", "1"), size=100, style=marker_style)
line2 = axes.plot(x, y2)
m2 = axes.scatterplot(x[3::10], y2[3::10], marker=("o", "2"), size=100, style=marker_style)
line3 = axes.plot(x, y3)
m3 = axes.scatterplot(x[6::10], y3[6::10], marker=("o", "3"), size=100, style=marker_style)

Note that the style information that we’re using in the above example is controlling just the appearance of the marker - the appearance of the labels is controlled by a separate “label_style” argument:

marker_style = {"fill":"black"}
label_style = {"fill":"white"}

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(width=500, height=300)
axes = canvas.axes()
line1 = axes.plot(x, y1)
m1 = axes.scatterplot(x[::10], y1[::10], marker=("o", "1"), size=100, style=marker_style, label_style=label_style)
line2 = axes.plot(x, y2)
m2 = axes.scatterplot(x[3::10], y2[3::10], marker=("o", "2"), size=100, style=marker_style, label_style=label_style)
line3 = axes.plot(x, y3)
m3 = axes.scatterplot(x[6::10], y3[6::10], marker=("o", "3"), size=100, style=marker_style, label_style=label_style)

Rendering¶

In interactive environments such as IPython, Toyplot’s autorender feature automatically renders a canvas onto the notebook page using Toyplot’s preferred HTML+SVG representation. If you’re working in a noninterative environment, you’ll need to explicitly tell Toyplot how and when to render your canvas, using one of Toyplot’s rendering backends. For example, if you’re using Toyplot from an interactive (vanilla) Python shell, you could use the toyplot.browser backend to display a canvas in a new web browser window, using the same HTML+SVG representation:

import toyplot.browser
toyplot.browser.show(canvas)

This will open a new browser window containing your figure, with all of Toyplot’s interaction and features intact. There are also several other backends that you can use to produce alternate formats, say, for inclusion in a paper:

import toyplot.pdf
toyplot.pdf.render(canvas, "figure1.pdf")

import toyplot.ps
toyplot.ps.render(canvas, "figure1.ps")

import toyplot.png
toyplot.png.render(canvas, "figure1.png")

You can also override the default autorender behavior. For example, if you prefer static images to Toyplot’s default HTML+SVG figures, you could specify the PNG backend when you create a canvas (note that the static image won’t provide any of Toyplot’s interactive functionality):

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(300, 300, autorender="png")
axes = canvas.axes()

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(300, 300, autorender=False)

... of course, it’s up to you to render your canvas somewhere in this case.

Axes¶

So far, we’ve created a default set of axes in each of the preceeding examples, and called methods on the axes to add marks to the canvas. The reason we explicitly create axes in Toyplot (instead of simply adding marks to the canvas directly) is that it allows us to have multiple axes on a single canvas:

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(600, 300)
axes = canvas.axes(grid=(1, 2, 0))
mark = axes.plot(x, y2)
axes = canvas.axes(grid=(1, 2, 1))
mark = axes.plot(x, y3)

The grid argument allows us to easily position each set of axes on a regular grid that covers the canvas. Note that you can control the axes position on the grid in a variety of ways:

  • (rows, columns, n)
    • fill cell \(n\) (in left-to-right, top-to-bottom order) of an \(M \times N\) grid.
  • (rows, columns, i, j)
    • fill cell \(i,j\) of an \(M \times N\) grid.
  • (rows, columns, i, rowspan, j, colspan)
    • fill cells \([i, i + rowspan), [j, j + colspan)\) of an \(M \times N\) grid.

You can also use the gutter argument to control the space between cells in the grid. For example:

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(400, 400)
axes = canvas.axes(grid=(3, 3, 0, 0), gutter=15) # Upper-left cell
axes = canvas.axes(grid=(3, 3, 2, 2), gutter=15) # Lower-right cell
axes = canvas.axes(grid=(3, 3, 0, 1, 1, 2), gutter=15) # Upper-right 1x2 cells
axes = canvas.axes(grid=(3, 3, 1, 2, 0, 2), gutter=15) # Lower-left 2x2 cells

Let’s explore some of the many attributes that can alter the behavior of our axes. For example, Toyplot axes include builtin support for labels:

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(300, 300)
axes = canvas.axes(label="Toyplot User Growth", xlabel="Days", ylabel="Users")
mark = axes.plot(x, y2)

Similarly, we scan specify minimum and maximum values for each axis - for example, if we wanted the previous figure to include \(y = 0\):

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(300, 300)
axes = canvas.axes(label="Toyplot User Growth", xlabel="Days", ylabel="Users", ymin=0)
mark = axes.plot(x, y2)

We can also specify logarithmic scales for each axis:

x = numpy.linspace(-1000, 1000)

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(700, 700)

axes = canvas.axes(grid=(2, 2, 1, 0), xscale="linear", yscale="linear", gutter=20)
line = axes.plot(x, x)
points = axes.scatterplot(x, x)

axes = canvas.axes(grid=(2, 2, 1, 1), xscale="log", yscale="linear", gutter=20)
line = axes.plot(x, x)
points = axes.scatterplot(x, x)

axes = canvas.axes(grid=(2, 2, 0, 0), xscale="linear", yscale="log", gutter=20)
line = axes.plot(x, x)
points = axes.scatterplot(x, x)

axes = canvas.axes(grid=(2, 2, 0, 1), xscale="log", yscale="log", gutter=20)
line = axes.plot(x, x)
points = axes.scatterplot(x, x)

Note that Toyplot handles negative values correctly, and provides sensible results for values in the range \(-1 < x < 1\) by rendering them using a small linear region around the origin.

Animation¶

Toyplot can also create animated figures, by recording changes to a figure over time. Assume you’ve setup the following scatterplot:

x = numpy.random.normal(size=100)
y = numpy.random.normal(size=len(x))

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(300, 300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.scatterplot(x, y, size=100)

Suppose we want to show the order in which the samples were drawn from some distribution. We can use toyplot.Canvas.animate() to add a sequence of animation frames to the canvas. We pass the number of frames and a callback function as arguments, and the callback function will be called once per frame with a single frame argument. The callback uses the frame object to retrieve information about the frame and record any changes that should be made to the canvas at that frame. In the example below, we set the opacity of each scatterplot datum to 5% in the first frame, then change back to 100% over the course of the animation:

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(300, 300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.scatterplot(x, y, size=100)

def callback(frame):
    if frame.index() == 0:
        for i in range(len(x)):
            frame.set_datum_style(mark, i, style={"opacity":0.05})
    else:
        frame.set_datum_style(mark, frame.index() - 1, style={"opacity":1.0})
canvas.animate(len(x) + 1, callback)

Let’s try animating something other than a datum style - in the following example, we add a text mark to the canvas, and use it to display information about the frame:

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(300, 300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.scatterplot(x, y, size=100)
text = canvas.text(150, 20, "", style={"text-anchor":"middle"})

def callback(frame):
    frame.set_mark_text(text, str(frame))
    if frame.index() == 0:
        for i in range(len(x)):
            frame.set_datum_style(mark, i, style={"opacity":0.05})
    else:
        frame.set_datum_style(mark, frame.index() - 1, style={"opacity":1.0})
canvas.animate(len(x) + 1, callback)

Note from this example that each frame has a zero-based frame index, along with begin and end times, which are measured in seconds. If you look closely, you’ll see that the difference in begin and end times is 0.03 seconds for each frame, which corresponds to a default 30 frames per second. If we want to control the framerate, we can pass a (frames, framerate) tuple when we call toyplot.Canvas.animate() (note that the playback is slower, and the times for the frames are changed):

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(300, 300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.scatterplot(x, y, size=100)
text = canvas.text(150, 20, "", style={"text-anchor":"middle"})

def callback(frame):
    frame.set_mark_text(text, str(frame))
    if frame.index() == 0:
        for i in range(len(x)):
            frame.set_datum_style(mark, i, style={"opacity":0.05})
    else:
        frame.set_datum_style(mark, frame.index() - 1, style={"opacity":1.0})
canvas.animate((len(x) + 1, 10), callback)

Sometimes the callback approach to animation is awkward, particularly if you simply have a one-time “event” that needs to happen in the middle of the animation. In this case, you can use toyplot.Canvas.time() to record changes for individual frames:

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(300, 300)
axes = canvas.axes()
mark = axes.scatterplot(x, y, size=100)
text = canvas.text(150, 20, "", style={"text-anchor":"middle"})
text2 = canvas.text(150, 50, "Halfway There!", style={"font-size":"16px", "font-weight":"bold", "fill":"blue", "text-anchor":"middle"})

def callback(frame):
    frame.set_mark_text(text, str(frame))
    if frame.index() == 0:
        for i in range(len(x)):
            frame.set_datum_style(mark, i, style={"opacity":0.05})
    else:
        frame.set_datum_style(mark, frame.index() - 1, style={"opacity":1.0})
canvas.animate((len(x) + 1, 10), callback)
canvas.time(0, 0.1).set_mark_style(text2, {"opacity":0.0})
canvas.time(5, 5.1).set_mark_style(text2, {"opacity":1.0})

Note that when you combine toyplot.Canvas.animate() and toyplot.Canvas.time(), you don’t have to force the “frames” to line-up ... you can record events in any order and at any point in time, whether there are existing frames at those times or not. In fact, you could call toyplot.Canvas.animate() multiple times, if you wanted to animate events happening at different rates:

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(100, 100, style={"background-color":"ivory"})
t1 = canvas.text(50, 33, "1 hz", style={"text-anchor":"middle"})
t2 = canvas.text(50, 66, "2 hz", style={"text-anchor":"middle"})
def blink(mark):
    def callback(frame):
        frame.set_mark_style(mark, {"opacity":frame.index() % 2.0})
    return callback
canvas.animate((10, 2), blink(t1))
canvas.animate((20, 4), blink(t2))

Using transition properties in your styles can smooth-out the animation by avoiding instantaneous changes:

canvas = toyplot.Canvas(100, 100, style={"background-color":"ivory"})
t1 = canvas.text(50, 33, "1 hz", style={"text-anchor":"middle", "transition":"opacity 0.5s"})
t2 = canvas.text(50, 66, "2 hz", style={"text-anchor":"middle", "transition":"opacity 0.25s"})
def blink(mark):
    def callback(frame):
        frame.set_mark_style(mark, {"opacity":frame.index() % 2.0})
    return callback
canvas.animate((10, 2), blink(t1))
canvas.animate((20, 4), blink(t2))
